## Security Ontology

### Security Entity Classification

#### 1. Security Subjects
```
SecuritySubjects
├── Users
│   ├── SystemAdministrator
│   ├── ApplicationUser
│   └── ServiceAccount
├── Processes
│   ├── SystemProcesses
│   ├── ContainerProcesses
│   └── ApplicationProcesses
└── Systems
    ├── HostSystem
    ├── ContainerSystem
    └── DatabaseSystem
```

#### 2. Security Objects
```
SecurityObjects
├── Data
│   ├── ConfigurationData
│   ├── UserData
│   ├── SystemData
│   └── LogData
├── Resources
│   ├── FileSystemResources
│   ├── NetworkResources
│   ├── ComputeResources
│   └── DatabaseResources
└── Services
    ├── ApplicationServices
    ├── SystemServices
    └── NetworkServices
```

#### 3. Security Operations
```
SecurityOperations
├── Access Operations
│   ├── Read
│   ├── Write
│   ├── Execute
│   └── Delete
├── Administrative Operations
│   ├── Create
│   ├── Modify
│   ├── Configure
│   └── Monitor
└── Security Operations
    ├── Authenticate
    ├── Authorize
    ├── Audit
    └── Encrypt
```

### Security Relationships

#### Access Control Relationships
```
Subject ACCESSES Object VIA Operation UNDER Policy
Administrator ACCESSES SystemData VIA Read UNDER AdministrativePolicy
ContainerProcess ACCESSES HostResources VIA None UNDER IsolationPolicy
ApplicationUser ACCESSES UserData VIA CRUD UNDER AuthorizationPolicy
```

#### Trust Relationships
```
HostSystem TRUSTS ContainerSystem WITHIN IsolationBoundary
ContainerSystem TRUSTS ApplicationProcesses WITHIN ProcessBoundary
SystemAdministrator TRUSTS SystemConfiguration WITHIN AdministrativeScope
```

#### Security Flow Relationships
```
SensitiveData FLOWS THROUGH EncryptedChannel
LogData FLOWS TO SecureStorage
UserInput FLOWS THROUGH ValidationGateway
SystemOutput FLOWS THROUGH RedactionFilter
```

### Security Patterns

#### 1. Defense in Depth Pattern
```
DefenseInDepthPattern
├── Layer1: InputValidation
├── Layer2: ContainerIsolation
├── Layer3: ProcessSandboxing
├── Layer4: NetworkSegmentation
├── Layer5: DataEncryption
└── Layer6: AuditLogging
```

#### 2. Least Privilege Pattern
```
LeastPrivilegePattern
├── Principle: MinimalRequiredAccess
├── Application:
│   ├── ContainerProcesses → MinimalHostAccess
│   ├── ApplicationUsers → MinimalDataAccess
│   └── SystemServices → MinimalResourceAccess
└── Enforcement: DynamicPrivilegeRevocation
```

#### 3. Secure by Default Pattern
```
SecureByDefaultPattern
├── Principle: DefaultDeny
├── Application:
│   ├── NetworkAccess → DefaultDenied
│   ├── FileSystemAccess → DefaultRestricted
│   └── ResourceAccess → DefaultLimited
└── Override: ExplicitPermissionRequired
```

### Security Constraints

#### Confidentiality Constraints
```
SensitiveData MUST NOT BE LoggedInPlaintext
UserCredentials MUST BE EncryptedAtRest
SystemSecrets MUST NOT BE ExposedInEnvironment
PrivateKeys MUST BE ProtectedByHardwareSecurity
```

#### Integrity Constraints
```
ConfigurationFiles MUST BE VerifiedBeforeUse
ExecutableCode MUST BE SignatureValidated
DatabaseTransactions MUST BE AtomicAndConsistent
LogEntries MUST BE TamperEvident
```

#### Availability Constraints
```
SystemServices MUST BE ResistantToDoSAttacks
CriticalOperations MUST HAVE FailoverMechanisms
DataBackups MUST BE RegularAndTested
RecoveryProcedures MUST BE AutomatedAndValidated
```

